NAME
       itoa - Convert an integer to a string

SYNOPSIS
       #include <stdlib.h>

       char *itoa(int n);

DESCRIPTION
       The itoa() function allocates and returns a new string representing the integer 'n'. The memory for the string is allocated using malloc(3).

PARAMETERS
       n: The integer to convert.

RETURN VALUE
       The string representing the integer 'n'.
       NULL if the allocation fails.

EXTERNAL FUNCTIONS
       malloc(3) - allocate dynamic memory

NOTES
       Negative numbers are handled, and the resulting string represents the absolute value of the input integer.

       The caller is responsible for freeing the allocated memory using free(3) when it is no longer needed.

EXAMPLES
       char *result_str = itoa(-42);
       // result_str is now "-42"

SEE ALSO
       malloc(3), free(3)

